docs.abstract: The virus outbreak supercharged a continuing shift in the markets, with a few giant companies now exerting the most influence over the direction of stocks since the tech boom.
docs.snippet: The virus outbreak supercharged a continuing shift in the markets, with a few giant companies now exerting the most influence over the direction of stocks since the tech boom.
docs.lead_paragraph: An economic downturn almost always favors giants like Microsoft, Apple and Amazon, the country’s three most valuable companies. But the demand for their shares has only been amplified by a crisis that seems almost tailor-made for their future success.

headline.main: Investors Bet Giant Companies Will Dominate After Crisis

docs.abstract: A computer with a good internet connection, communication apps and entertainment are the only tech we really need, ever.
docs.snippet: A computer with a good internet connection, communication apps and entertainment are the only tech we really need, ever.
docs.lead_paragraph: It has been weeks since the coronavirus brought our lives to a halt, shutting down our schools, offices and gyms. Stuck at home, we have had nothing but time to reflect on the things that matter.

headline.main: The Virus Revealed Our Essential Tech (and Weeded Out the Excess)
headline.print_headline: Cooped Up With Tech, an Epiphany

docs.abstract: The ruling is another court victory by French unions against Amazon in a battle over workplace safety.
docs.snippet: The ruling is another court victory by French unions against Amazon in a battle over workplace safety.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Amazon lost an appeal on Friday of a French court decision ordering the e-commerce giant to stop delivering nonessential items in France during the coronavirus crisis to protect workers, raising questions about the immediate future of its business in the country.

headline.main: Amazon Loses Appeal of French Order to Stop Selling Nonessential Items
headline.print_headline: Amazon Loses Another Round In French Court

docs.abstract: Cargo capacity has been expanding at some airports, disturbing the peace and routines of people who live nearby. Official channels offer scant recourse.
docs.snippet: Cargo capacity has been expanding at some airports, disturbing the peace and routines of people who live nearby. Official channels offer scant recourse.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last time Congress approved legislation dealing with airport noise complaints was 30 years ago, when the biggest concern was older, inefficient planes.

headline.main: As Online Buying Surges, So Do Noisy Cargo Flights
headline.print_headline: Online Buying Surges (as Does the Noise)

docs.abstract: The attorney general said in a letter that Amazon may have violated laws in firing a Staten Island worker who led a protest against the company.
docs.snippet: The attorney general said in a letter that Amazon may have violated laws in firing a Staten Island worker who led a protest against the company.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Amazon may have violated federal worker safety laws and New York State’s whistle-blower protections when it fired an employee from its Staten Island warehouse who protested the company’s response to the coronavirus outbreak, according to a letter the office of the New York attorney general, Letitia James, sent the company last week.

headline.main: New York Attorney General Scrutinizes Amazon for Firing Warehouse Worker

docs.lead_paragraph: As if in the darkest children’s fable ever told, the undisputed winner of the current plague turns out to be the man who already had everything, the king whose empire appears intent on consuming the entire map. This week Jeff Bezos, the richest man on earth, saw the year’s first financial quarter close with Amazon stock up more than 5 percent, trading at $1,950 a share, during a period in which the Dow had its worst overall quarter since 1987.

headline.main: ‘We Didn’t Sign Up for This’: Amazon Workers on the Front Lines

docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — At the end of February, Jeff Bezos, Amazon’s chief executive, and his girlfriend, Lauren Sanchez, were in France discussing climate change with President Emmanuel Macron at the Élysée Palace and celebrating atop the Eiffel Tower with the designer Diane von Furstenberg. Days later, paparazzi spotted the couple grabbing dinner at Carbone in New York.

headline.main: Bezos Takes Back the Wheel at Amazon

docs.abstract: Our online habits are changing, likely for good. This could make tech companies even more muscular.

docs.lead_paragraph: We need technology to keep us supplied, connected and informed in this pandemic. And these changes may stick with us. Are we giving too much power to tech companies now — and possibly forever?

headline.main: The Pandemic Feeds Tech Companies’ Power
